  <Fragment slot="headline">How Much House Can I Afford? A Practical Mortgage Guide</Fragment>

  <p>Buying a home is not just about what a bank might approve. It is about what you can comfortably pay month after month.</p>
  <p>The real answer depends on your income, current debts, down payment, loan term, taxes, insurance, and your own comfort level.</p>

  <h2>Quick Answer</h2>
  <p>A practical home budget starts with the monthly payment, not the listing price. Work backward from what you can safely afford each month, then estimate the house price that fits.</p>

  <h2>The Main Factors</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Household income</li>
    <li>Existing monthly debt</li>
    <li>Down payment amount</li>
    <li>Interest rate</li>
    <li>Property taxes and homeowners insurance</li>
    <li>Loan term, usually 15 or 30 years</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Why Monthly Payment Matters More Than Purchase Price</h2>
  <p>Two homes with the same price can lead to very different monthly costs if taxes, insurance, interest rate, or down payment are different.</p>

  <h2>How to Estimate Affordability</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Estimate your monthly take-home pay.</li>
    <li>Subtract debt, savings goals, and fixed living costs.</li>
    <li>Choose a realistic monthly housing budget.</li>
    <li>Use that payment to estimate the home price range.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Best Tools to Use</h2>
  <p>Use the <a href="https://mycalcstool.com/en/salary-calculator"><strong>Salary Calculator</strong></a> to estimate take-home pay, then use the <a href="https://mycalcstool.com/en/mortgage-calculator"><strong>Mortgage Calculator</strong></a> to test different home prices, down payments, and loan terms.</p>

  <h2>Final Takeaway</h2>
  <p>The best home budget is one that still leaves room for saving, emergencies, and normal life. A lender approval amount is not the same as a comfortable budget.</p>
</BlogLayout>
